{{no footnotes|date= October 2018}} [[File:Bhujangasana Yoga-Asana Nina-Mel.jpg|thumb|right|Bhujangasana]]
{{IndicText}}
'''Bhujangasana''' ({{IPA-sa|bʱʊ.ɟ͡ʝəŋ.gɑːsə.nə}};<ref>{{cite book |last1=Budilovsky |first1=Joan |last2=Adamson |first2=Eve |title=The complete idiot's guide to yoga |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b5pE8-Oyly0C |accessdate=11 April 2011 |edition=2 |year=2000 |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-02-863970-3 |page=156}}</ref> {{lang-sa|भुजङ्गासन}}; [[IAST]]: ''Bhujaṅgāsana'') or '''Cobra Pose'''<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.yogajournal.com/poses/471 | title = Yoga Journal&nbsp;– Cobra Pose | accessdate = 2011-04-09}}</ref> is a back-bending yoga [[asana]]<ref>How To Do Cobra Pose https://www.verywell.com/cobra-pose-bhujangasana-3567067</ref>.
==Etymology== The name comes from the Sanskrit words ''bhujanga'' meaning "snake" or "serpent" and ''asana'' (आसन) meaning "posture" or "seat".
From a [[Prone position|prone]] position with [[Palm (hand)|palms]] and [[legs]] on the floor, the [[chest]] is lifted. This asana resembles a serpent with its hood raised. Cobra Pose or Bhujangasana is part of the sequence of yoga postures in Padma Sadhana and Surya Namaskar or Sun Salutation. Bhujangasana is pronounced as BHU-jung-AAHS-uh-nuh. Bhujang = Snake (Cobra); Asana = Posture or Pose
To get into this position, come onto the ground on your stomach. Place both palms under the shoulders. Draw your elbows towards your side body. Keeping the gaze down towards your mat, maintain a neutral neck. As you inhale, push down through the palms and lift the chest, engaging the core and lifting the quads off the ground. Tops of the feet should still press into the ground. The neck remains neutral and the gaze stays on the ground.{{cn|date=September 2018}}
==Benefits == Bhujangasana may strengthen the [[vertebral column|spine]], stretch the chest, shoulders, and abdomen, firm the [[buttocks]], remove lethargy relieve stress and fatigue and makes practitioner active. Traditional texts say that Bhujangasana increases body heat, destroys disease, and awakens [[Kundalini energy|kundalini]]. The practitioner gets benefited by the qualities that a cobra have i.e. a good digestion, supple body, activeness, and longevity.
==Cautions== Common postural errors during this asana include overarching the neck and lower back. One recommendation is to keep the gaze directed down at the floor and focus on bringing movement into the area between the shoulder blades (the thoracic area, or middle back).<ref>[http://www.yogajournal.com/for_teachers/2551 Yoga for Chronic Pain, Part I], By Timothy McCall, M.D.</ref>
==Follow-up asanas== Bhujangasana is followed by [[Salabhasana]]. In [[Surya Namaskar]], it precedes [[Adho Mukha Svanasana]].
