[[ru:Растягивающие асаны#Бхуджангасана]]

'''''Bodhipathapradīpa''''' (''A Lamp for the Path to Awakening'') is a [[Buddhist texts|Buddhist text]] composed in [[Sanskrit]] by the 11th-century teacher [[Atiśa]] and widely considered his [[Masterpiece|magnum opus]]. The text reconciles the doctrines of many various Buddhist schools and philosophies, and is notable for the introduction of the three levels of spiritual aspiration: lesser, middling and superior,<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Williams|first=Paul|authorlink=Paul Williams (philosopher)|title=Mahayana Buddhism: The Doctrinal Foundations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z3FuzkBnOxAC|date=11 July 2008|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-25057-8}}</ref> which in turn became the foundation for the [[Lamrim]] tradition. This text was translated into Tibetan as ''Byang chub lam gyi sgron ma''.{{sfn|Günther|2001|p=17}}

